There appears to be light at the end of the tunnel, following the approval of several vaccines.
However, the revelation that new strains of coronavirus are circulating in the UK, South Africa and Nigeria could complicate efforts aimed at controlling the deadly virus.
According to WHO and Africa Centres for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), these strains are highly transmissible and could be prevalent in many countries. Admittedly, identification of these variants in real time is a testament to a remarkable contribution of modern science.





 It paves the way for investigation of the variants with an aim to understand their biological characteristics that distinguish them from the original strain.
It would also allow for further work to determine if these variants bring about severity of the disease and changes in antibody response or vaccine efficacy.
Foreign environments
That the original coronavirus has mutated to more transmissible variants is not a surprise to scientists who study viruses. Coronaviruses fall under the RNA type. RNA viruses have shorter generation time due to extremely high replication levels, which operates in an environment that is prone to errors. This, inevitably, results in high mutation rates that are linked with increased evolvability and virulence.



