These traits equip viruses with the ability to adapt to foreign environments in other organisms, including humans, where they cause transmissible infections. As a result, RNA viruses have been implicated in the most devastating pandemics, including two of the worst — Spanish flu (1918-1920) and Aids (1981- to the present).
Recent applications of new technology in biology have led to the development of high-throughput sequencing tools that can accurately determine the order of molecules that make up genome of viruses and other living organisms, at an unprecedented speed.
These tools have improved the understanding of biology at a genomic level, allowing changes, including, but not limited to, mutations to be identified.
Employing these tools, scientists were able to sequence and analyse the complete genome of the novel coronavirus a few months after it was reported, unearthing key features that facilitated vaccine development.
